s21.q4cdn.com/399680738/files/doc_financials/2023/q1/META-Q1-2023-Earnings-=
Call-Transcript.pdf ) (this excerpt is from a two-part question; I=E2=80=99=
m only including the relevant second part):

*And then on the regulatory front, can you just help explain how changes to=
 the transatlantic data transfer rules may impact your European business as=
 it goes into effect? Just trying to get a sense if we have a potentially I=
DFA situation with a signal loss here again, thank you.*

*CFO Susan Li:* So first I want to emphasize we continue to be hopeful that=
 the new E.U.-U.S. privacy framework will be implemented before a deadline =
for a suspension. But if it comes to that, there=E2=80=99s a lot that we do=
n=E2=80=99t know in terms of the specifics of a final order and how long a =
suspension order would last, which would be important variables in determin=
ing the overall impact. What we do know is that roughly 10% of worldwide ad=
 revenue comes from ads delivered to Facebook users in E.U. countries. But =
there are more details that we would need to understand, including the impa=
ct on advertisers in E.U. countries before we=E2=80=99d be able to really p=
rovide a more accurate or fulsome estimate of that impact.

Yesterday I noted that Meta wouldn=E2=80=99t be abandoning the E.U. over a =
$1 billion fine, plus however much it might cost to abide by the E.U.=E2=80=
=99s various rules and regulations, given it made $25.79 billion in Europe =
last year: that=E2=80=99s 22% of revenue. That, you will note, is a much bi=
gger number than =E2=80=9Croughly 10%=E2=80=9D, which is to say that it app=
ears that Meta makes more money in the non-E.U. European countries than it =
makes in the E.U. as a whole; =E2=80=9Croughly 10%=E2=80=9D of its 2022 rev=
enue is only $11.7 billion.

That=E2=80=99s a surprisingly low number, and increases the credibility Met=
a=E2=80=99s threat to potentially leave the market. I=E2=80=99m still skept=
ical, to be clear, because the value to a social network goes beyond ad rev=
enue: Meta users in the rest of the world (including the U.K.) have a bette=
r product by virtue of people in the E.U. being on the platform. That value=
 goes the other way, of course: Meta=E2=80=99s platforms are valuable to E.=
U. citizens because the rest of the world is already on them. That, by exte=
nsion, raises an interesting possibility: could Meta makes its platforms su=
bscription-based in the E.U.?

It=E2=80=99s not as outlandish a proposition as you might think; here are M=
eta=E2=80=99s relevant numbers by region (for last quarter):

DAU MAU Ad Revenue ARPU U.S. & Canada 200 269 $12,710 $48.85 Europe 307 411=
 $6,269 $15.51 Asia-Pacific 873 1,324 $5,893 $4.52 Rest of World 657 986 $3=
,229 $3.35

Keep in mind, though, that more than half of European revenue comes from no=
n-E.U. countries, even though those countries have a combined population (3=
02 million) that is 2/3 the size of the E.U.=E2=80=99s (447 million). If we=
 incorporate Li=E2=80=99s 10% figure and split active users proportionally,=
 we can separate the E.U. and the non-E.U. segments in the table above:

DAU MAU Ad Revenue ARPU U.S. & Canada 200 269 $12,710 $48.85 E.U. 183 245 $=
2,810 $11.47 Non-E.U. 124 166 $3,459 $20.84 Asia-Pacific 873 1,324 $5,893 $=
4.52 Rest of World 657 986 $3,229 $3.35

My understanding is the U.K. is the biggest driver of Meta revenue in Europ=
e, but I didn=E2=80=99t realize just how much the E.U. trailed; in fact, E.=
U. ARPU is closer to Asia-Pacific and the Rest of World than they are to th=
e U.S. & Canada or even non-E.U. countries (which again, suggests that the =
U.K. is probably closer to that U.S. & Canada mark).

Now keep in mind these are quarterly figures; Meta would need to charge aro=
und $5/month to make up that revenue (including App Store fees), but of cou=
rse a lot of people would drop off, which means that number would be even h=
igher in reality; that=E2=80=99s obviously not going to happen and besides,=
 this is a social network! Of course Meta isn=E2=80=99t going to charge for=
 a subscription. Instead the company is giving E.U. users the option of fil=
ling out a web form to opt-out of personalized advertising ( https://www.ws=
j.com/articles/meta-to-let-users-opt-out-of-some-targeted-ads-but-only-in-e=
urope-44b20b6d ) ; it remains to be seen if that holds up in Court.

Still, I thought this was a useful exercise; I never realized just how low =
E.U. ARPU was, which also helps explain the E.U.=E2=80=99s approach: Meta c=
learly isn=E2=80=99t that important to E.U. businesses, so it=E2=80=99s no =
big deal to E.U. regulators if they make using Meta for business less usefu=
l.

The Supreme Court and Section 230
---------------------------------

From CNBC ( https://www.cnbc.com/2023/05/18/supreme-court-declines-to-addre=
ss-tech-liability-shield-in-google-ruling.html ) :

The Supreme Court declined to address the legal liability shield that prote=
cts tech platforms from being held responsible for their users=E2=80=99 pos=
ts, the court said in an unsigned opinion Thursday. The decision leaves in =
place, for now, a broad liability shield that protects companies like Twitt=
er, Meta=E2=80=99s Facebook and Instagram as well as Google=E2=80=99s YouTu=
be from being held liable for their users=E2=80=99 speech on their platform=
s. The court=E2=80=99s decisions in these cases will serve as a big sigh of=
 relief for tech platforms for now, but many members of Congress are still =
itching to reform the legal liability shield.

In the case, Gonzalez v. Google, the court said it would =E2=80=9Cdecline t=
o address the application=E2=80=9D of Section 230 of the Communications Dec=
ency Act, the law that protects platforms from their users=E2=80=99 speech =
and also allows the services to moderate or remove users=E2=80=99 posts. Th=
e court said it made that decision because the complaint =E2=80=9Cappears t=
o state little, if any, plausible claim for relief.=E2=80=9D The Supreme Co=
urt will send the case back to a lower court to reconsider in light of its =
decision on a separate but similar case, Twitter v. Taamneh.

In that case, the family of an American victim of a terrorist attack sought=
 to hold Twitter accountable under anti-terrorism law for allegedly aiding =
and abetting the attack by failing to take enough action against terrorist =
content on its platform. In a decision written by Justice Clarence Thomas, =
the court ruled that such a claim could not be brought under that statute.

This is a technically correct reading of the Supreme Court=E2=80=99s decisi=
ons in these cases; the actual opinion in Twitter v. Taamneh , though, whic=
h was not about Section 230, does in fact bode very well for Section 230 go=
ing forward. I wrote about Gonzalez v. Google the week it was argued ( http=
s://stratechery.com/2023/section-230-in-the-supreme-court-reach-and-speech-=
the-first-amendment-and-u-s-speech-controls/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI=
1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhd=
WQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJlbnQiOnsidXJpIjpbImh0dHBzOi8v=
c3RyYXRlY2hlcnkuY29tLzIwMjMvc2VjdGlvbi0yMzAtaW4tdGhlLXN1cHJlbWUtY291cnQtcmV=
hY2gtYW5kLXNwZWVjaC10aGUtZmlyc3QtYW1lbmRtZW50LWFuZC11LXMtc3BlZWNoLWNvbnRyb2=
xzLyJdfSwiZXhwIjoxNjg3NDMzNTUwLCJpYXQiOjE2ODQ4NDE1NTAsImlzcyI6Imh0dHBzOi8vc=
